About

In this notebook I implement a basic SIR model.

SIR

From Wikipedia: SIR.

The SIR model without vital dynamics:

The dynamics of an epidemic, for example the flu, are often much faster than the dynamics of birth and death, therefore, birth and death are often omitted in simple compartmental models. The SIR system without so-called vital dynamics (birth and death, sometimes called demography) described above can be expressed by the following set of ordinary differential equations:
\begin{aligned} &{\frac {dS}{dt}}=-{\frac {\beta IS}{N}},\\ &{\frac {dI}{dt}}={\frac {\beta IS}{N}}-\gamma I,\\ &{\frac {dR}{dt}}=\gamma I, \end{aligned} 
import attr
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy.integrate import solve_ivp
import seaborn as sns
sns.set(style="ticks")

@attr.s
class SIR(object):
    N = attr.ib(converter=int)
    I = attr.ib(converter=float)
    beta = attr.ib(converter=float)
    gamma = attr.ib(converter=float)
    days = attr.ib(converter=int, default=200)
    
    S = attr.ib(init=False, converter=float)
    
    R = attr.ib(init=False, converter=float, default=0.0)
    
    
    def __attrs_post_init__(self):
        self.S = self.N - self.I - self.R
    
    
    @staticmethod
    def ode(t, y, beta, gamma, N):
        S, I, R = y
        
        new_cases = beta*S*I/N
        removed_cases = gamma*I
        S = -new_cases
        I = new_cases - removed_cases
        R = removed_cases

        y = (S,I,R)

        return y
    
    def solve_days(self):
        y = (self.S, self.I, self.R)
        return solve_ivp(SIR.ode, [0,self.days], y,t_eval=np.arange(0,self.days), args=(self.beta, self.gamma, self.N))

        
    def plot(self):
        sol = self.solve_days()
        df_sol = pd.DataFrame(sol.y.T, index=sol.t, columns=["Suspectible","Infected","Removed"])
        sns.lineplot(data=df_sol,)

m = SIR(5000,6,0.3,0.1)
display(m)
m.plot()

SIR(N=5000, I=6.0, beta=0.3, gamma=0.1, days=200, S=4994.0, R=0.0)
